cs.AI, cs.CL, cs.DB, cs.IR, cs.LG. 

The paper focuses on knowledge base construction (KBC) from richly formatted data, which involves extracting relations conveyed jointly via textual, structural, tabular, and visual expressions. This suggests that the paper could belong to several sub-categories related to natural language processing (NLP), machine learning (ML), and databases. 

cs.AI is the most likely category, as the paper describes a machine-learning-based KBC system that uses a deep-learning model to automatically capture the representation needed to extract relations from richly formatted data. 

cs.CL is also likely, as the paper deals with extracting relations from textual data and mentions the use of NLP techniques. 

cs.DB is another likely category, as the paper deals with constructing a knowledge base from structured data and mentions the use of a new data model to account for prevalent document-level relations and multimodality. 

cs.IR is also possible, as the paper deals with information retrieval from richly formatted data. 

cs.LG is the least likely category, but still possible, as the paper deals with developing a new programming model that enables users to convert domain expertise to meaningful signals of supervision for training a KBC system. This could be seen as a form of machine learning.
